Utterances.UttText: Gerry Cage is a 46 year old with hypertension who presents with chest pain.

He reports an episode of mid-sternal chest pain that he describes as a "deep ache and heavy" while he was walking while carrying heavy groceries 3 days ago which was non-radiating and lasted for 5-10 minutes.

Phrases.PhraseText: an episode of mid-sternal chest pain

Utterances.UttText: He also had lightheadedness during this episode and had to sit down and rest which resolved his pain.
He notes that for the past 4 months, he had several episodes of pain when he exerted himself which lasted a couple of seconds.
He also reports a feeling of "pressure" in his epigastrium after eating a heavy meal.
He denies fever, chills, nausea, vomiting, and shortness of breath.

Medical History: Hypertension, treated with Chlorthalidone and Lisinopril Family history: Mother - Pulmonary embolism in 60's, father - myocardial infarction in  40's and had a bypass surgery Social history: -Tobacco: Currently smokes tobacco 1 pack/day for past 20 years -Alcohol:3-4 glasses/week -Denies marijuana and drug use PE: -No chest wall tenderness, regular rate and rhythm, no edema swelling -Lungs: Clear to auscultation bilaterally  Assessment: Mr.

Phrases.PhraseText: had a bypass surgery Social history

Utterances.UttText: Cage is a 46 year old male with hypertension and 20 pack-year tobacco use who presents for mid-sternal chest pain with exertion.

Phrases.PhraseText: a 46 year old male with hypertension

Utterances.UttText: Vitals are significant for an elevated blood pressure of 150/92 , and physical exam does not reveal chest wall tenderness.

Phrases.PhraseText: significant for an elevated blood pressure of 150/92 ,

Utterances.UttText: Differential diagnosis of chest pain includes acute coronary syndrome due to pain with exertion and significant family history and risk factors of hypertension and tobacco use.

Phrases.PhraseText: acute coronary syndrome due to pain

Utterances.UttText: Other diagnosis include costochondritis which is unlikely due to lack of tenderness on palpation and pulmonary embolism which is unlikely due to recurring nature of pain with exertion.

Phrases.PhraseText: unlikely due to lack of tenderness
unlikely due to recurring nature of pain

Utterances.UttText: Biliary sludge/gallstones are a possibility due to epigastric pain after eating.

Phrases.PhraseText: a possibility due to epigastric pain

Utterances.UttText: Plan: -Get EKG while resting -Get labs - CBC, CMP, troponin -Schedule patient for stress test  -Get right upper quadrant ultrasound to check for gallstones in gallbladder
